Yeah, so in the late 1230s, early 1240s,

00:28:22.590 --> 00:28:25.770
the Mongols aren't defeated by anybody.

00:28:25.770 --> 00:28:28.650
The Batu Khan is not defeated by anybody.

00:28:28.650 --> 00:28:29.483
We'll talk about this.

00:28:29.483 --> 00:28:30.956
They have the stirrups,

00:28:30.956 --> 00:28:34.890
they have the encirclement
maneuvers, they have the calls.

00:28:34.890 --> 00:28:36.810
They're not defeated by anybody in Europe.

00:28:36.810 --> 00:28:40.260
They destroy every army,
European army, they touch.

00:28:40.260 --> 00:28:41.910
And that includes Kyiv,

00:28:43.980 --> 00:28:46.413
but it doesn't include France.

00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:48.690
Not because they couldn't have done it,

00:28:48.690 --> 00:28:49.890
but because at a certain point,

00:28:49.890 --> 00:28:53.130
the Batu Khan has to go
back for a succession issue.

00:28:53.130 --> 00:28:55.140
'Cause the main Khan has died.

00:28:55.140 --> 00:28:57.990
But if the Batu Khan gets to Paris,

00:28:57.990 --> 00:29:02.970
I mean, arguably no Renaissance,
no Age of Exploration.

00:29:02.970 --> 00:29:04.410
Probably some other part of the world

00:29:04.410 --> 00:29:06.840
carries out the Age of
Exploration, not the Europeans.

00:29:06.840 --> 00:29:09.210
And it's a very, very,
very different world.

00:29:09.210 --> 00:29:10.920
And that's just a matter
of one person dying.

00:29:10.920 --> 00:29:12.480
If one person had died a year later,

00:29:12.480 --> 00:29:15.453
we're probably looking at an
extremely different world.

00:29:16.634 --> 00:29:18.750
Not to say that the moment we're in

00:29:18.750 --> 00:29:20.340
is quite comparable to that.

00:29:20.340 --> 00:29:25.340
But it does strike me as
being significant that,

00:29:25.410 --> 00:29:27.360
and of course you can't
help but think about this

00:29:27.360 --> 00:29:28.650
when you're standing
in the middle of Kyiv,

00:29:28.650 --> 00:29:30.810
but it seems quite significant
that Russian soldiers

00:29:30.810 --> 00:29:35.673
do or don't get to Kyiv
in February of 2022.

00:29:36.660 --> 00:29:40.263
And it's really close. It's really close.

00:29:41.152 --> 00:29:44.820
The Russians land in
the Hostomel Airfield,

00:29:44.820 --> 00:29:46.680
and their plan is to land there,

00:29:46.680 --> 00:29:49.620
drop the paratroopers, drop
the special forces, go in,

00:29:49.620 --> 00:29:52.410
gather up the elite, kidnap
them, probably exterminate them.

00:29:52.410 --> 00:29:54.690
And that's part of the
plan to take over the city.

00:29:54.690 --> 00:29:56.133
And they get to Hostomel,

00:29:56.970 --> 00:30:00.540
which is only about 35
kilometers, 20 miles,

00:30:00.540 --> 00:30:01.560
from the center of Kyiv.

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:04.050
They get that far on the
first day of the war.

00:30:04.050 --> 00:30:07.350
They get that far, but
the Ukrainians stop them.

00:30:07.350 --> 00:30:08.727
There's a terrible battle around Hostomel

00:30:08.727 --> 00:30:11.490
and it goes on, but the
Ukrainians stop them.

00:30:11.490 --> 00:30:13.980
Bucha, which you probably heard of

00:30:13.980 --> 00:30:15.810
because of the atrocities,

00:30:15.810 --> 00:30:20.763
And, I saw Bucha very briefly too.

00:30:24.174 --> 00:30:26.777
It was also very, that was
also kind of interesting

00:30:26.777 --> 00:30:28.740
because the air raid
sirens went off in Bucha,

00:30:28.740 --> 00:30:31.290
and I was with the Ukrainian general

00:30:31.290 --> 00:30:33.990
and he was like, "Well, we
can always go to the basement

00:30:33.990 --> 00:30:36.927
of the church, if anything
actually happens."

00:30:38.490 --> 00:30:40.950
Bucha is basically a bedroom community.

00:30:40.950 --> 00:30:44.700
It's like 28 kilometers from Kyiv.

00:30:44.700 --> 00:30:45.533
It's a suburb.

00:30:46.980 --> 00:30:51.030
Irpin, where so many
buildings are destroyed,

00:30:51.030 --> 00:30:54.540
it's like a beautiful parked,
it's a really nice place.

00:30:54.540 --> 00:30:57.454
You might wanna, if you were
like going up in the world

00:30:57.454 --> 00:31:00.000
and you wanna have a nice
place and drive, commute,

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:01.440
the American dream.

00:31:01.440 --> 00:31:02.640
If you wanted to do that,

00:31:02.640 --> 00:31:04.350
Irpin would be a wonderful place to go.

00:31:04.350 --> 00:31:05.970
Now it's all shot up,

00:31:05.970 --> 00:31:07.590
and there's a huge pile of burned cars,

00:31:07.590 --> 00:31:09.360
and there building after
building was destroyed

00:31:09.360 --> 00:31:11.410
by Russian tanks as they were retreating.

00:31:12.360 --> 00:31:14.821
That's like 20 kilometers from Kyiv.

00:31:14.821 --> 00:31:17.700
And the same is true
going the other direction

00:31:17.700 --> 00:31:20.220
across the Dnieper towards Chernihiv.

00:31:20.220 --> 00:31:24.270
The Russians got very,
very, very close to Kyiv.

00:31:24.270 --> 00:31:26.580
But they didn't get to Kyiv.

00:31:26.580 --> 00:31:28.530
They didn't get that little difference,

00:31:30.660 --> 00:31:33.930
those last 15 miles of physical geography

00:31:33.930 --> 00:31:37.173
would seem to make a huge difference.

00:31:38.250 --> 00:31:41.520
And the way people react to the war

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:43.530
also has a great deal to do with

00:31:43.530 --> 00:31:45.360
how they understand the
geography around them.

00:31:45.360 --> 00:31:46.233
So for example,

00:31:47.999 --> 00:31:50.490
time after time after time,

00:31:50.490 --> 00:31:53.070
people who lived in Kyiv or other cities

00:31:53.070 --> 00:31:55.345
would say, when the war started,

00:31:55.345 --> 00:31:58.647
"i should go to the villages,
I should go to the suburbs."

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:00.630
That's a natural thought.

00:32:00.630 --> 00:32:02.280
Like, "They're gonna get to Kyiv,

00:32:03.450 --> 00:32:06.526
I should go to my dacha, I
should go to my grandmother's,

00:32:06.526 --> 00:32:09.717
I should go to my second house."

00:32:10.650 --> 00:32:13.440
But it was the villages actually
that took the punishment,

00:32:13.440 --> 00:32:15.480
time and time again.

00:32:15.480 --> 00:32:18.360
People from Kyiv went to Bucha and Irpin,

00:32:18.360 --> 00:32:19.530
because they thought Bucha and Irpin

00:32:19.530 --> 00:32:22.430
would be safer than Kyiv, which
turned out not to be true.

00:32:23.490 --> 00:32:27.240
A friend of mine who lives
close to the Dnieper,

00:32:27.240 --> 00:32:29.439
the Dnieper runs through Kyiv.

00:32:29.439 --> 00:32:31.350
And so, a friend of mine assumed

00:32:31.350 --> 00:32:34.740
that the Russians would
get as far as the river,

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:36.750
and the Ukrainians would
then blow the bridges,

00:32:36.750 --> 00:32:39.480
and then you only have
one direction to flee.

00:32:39.480 --> 00:32:44.373
So in moments like this, you're
thinking in terms of space.

00:32:45.870 --> 00:32:47.868
I wanted to go someplace besides Kyiv

00:32:47.868 --> 00:32:49.695
and Bucha and Irpin and Hostomel.

00:32:49.695 --> 00:32:51.420
I wanted to get outside of Kyiv Oblast.

00:32:51.420 --> 00:32:54.384
And so I went with a friend to Chernihiv,

00:32:54.384 --> 00:32:55.217
the Chernihiv Oblast,

00:32:55.217 --> 00:32:58.533
which is just basically due
north, a little bit east.

00:32:59.466 --> 00:33:03.450
Chernihiv is a fascinating city.

00:33:03.450 --> 00:33:04.700
We're gonna return to it.

00:33:05.880 --> 00:33:08.010
It might have been on one of your maps.

00:33:08.010 --> 00:33:09.120
The reason it was on one of your maps

00:33:09.120 --> 00:33:11.010
is that it's an old city.

00:33:11.010 --> 00:33:14.040
It's 500 years or so older than Moscow.

00:33:14.040 --> 00:33:16.920
It's been there for a very
long time. It's ancient.

00:33:16.920 --> 00:33:20.703
And it is an ancient
center also of scholarship,

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:24.870
of theology and of scholarship.

00:33:24.870 --> 00:33:27.810
Along with Kyiv, it was one
of the two great centers

00:33:27.810 --> 00:33:31.320
of religious, and intellectual
in general, disputation

00:33:31.320 --> 00:33:35.070
in what's now Ukraine.

00:33:35.070 --> 00:33:38.820
And one reason why I
have Chernihiv in mind

00:33:38.820 --> 00:33:42.990
is that this whole story
about the Kyiv and the Moscow

00:33:42.990 --> 00:33:44.010
and how it's all one place,

00:33:44.010 --> 00:33:47.430
that was actually invented
by a guy in Chernihiv.

00:33:47.430 --> 00:33:49.110
It was invented by one person.

00:33:49.110 --> 00:33:50.960
Like now, we all believe it.

00:33:50.960 --> 00:33:52.890
It has this incredible effect on-

00:33:52.890 --> 00:33:54.450
And the reason he invented it

00:33:54.450 --> 00:33:56.580
had everything to do with geography.

