the territory on the east of the Dnieper

00:34:35.460 --> 00:34:36.930
was going to be Russia,

00:34:36.930 --> 00:34:39.450
and west of the Dnieper
was going to be Poland.

00:34:39.450 --> 00:34:41.610
It was a little unclear
what that meant for Kyiv,

00:34:41.610 --> 00:34:43.320
because Kyiv was on both sides,

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:46.890
but eventually Kyiv
ended up being part of,

00:34:46.890 --> 00:34:48.949
being under control of, Moscow.

00:34:48.949 --> 00:34:51.300
And that meant Chernihiv was as well.

00:34:51.300 --> 00:34:54.690
So Kyiv and Chernihiv, which
are these major centers

00:34:54.690 --> 00:34:56.910
of European scholarship and thought,

00:34:56.910 --> 00:34:58.920
are now suddenly under
the control of Moscow,

00:34:58.920 --> 00:35:01.833
which has no centers of
scholarship and thought.

00:35:02.760 --> 00:35:05.640
And no, that's just a statement of fact.

00:35:05.640 --> 00:35:07.710
I mean, there aren't any universities,

00:35:07.710 --> 00:35:10.863
there aren't any academies
in Moscow at that time.

00:35:14.130 --> 00:35:16.833
So Lazar Baranovych was
a very intelligent guy,

00:35:17.880 --> 00:35:20.730
one of the great theologians of his time,

00:35:20.730 --> 00:35:23.850
and used to enjoying a certain
amount of personal influence,

00:35:23.850 --> 00:35:25.050
it should be said.

00:35:25.050 --> 00:35:28.560
And when Chernihiv and
Kyiv fall under Moscow,

00:35:28.560 --> 00:35:30.270
he makes a play.

00:35:30.270 --> 00:35:31.650
And see if you could think of a play

00:35:31.650 --> 00:35:33.540
which is as good as this play.

00:35:33.540 --> 00:35:34.593
He says,

00:35:36.608 --> 00:35:41.107
to the fellow Orthodox
clergy in Moscow, he says,

00:35:41.107 --> 00:35:45.303
"You know what? We're
actually all one country.

00:35:46.590 --> 00:35:49.560
And the history of your
country, that one in Moscow,

00:35:49.560 --> 00:35:52.290
it actually begins in Kyiv."

00:35:52.290 --> 00:35:53.880
And this was news to the people in Moscow.

00:35:53.880 --> 00:35:54.960
This had not occurred to them.

00:35:54.960 --> 00:35:57.180
This was not their story
of themselves at the time.

00:35:57.180 --> 00:35:59.437
But Baranovych said,

00:35:59.437 --> 00:36:02.037
"Your history actually starts with Kyiv."

00:36:02.880 --> 00:36:04.050
And of course, why does he say that?

00:36:04.050 --> 00:36:07.623
Because that makes Kyiv really important.

00:36:08.790 --> 00:36:12.657
Because, so suddenly Ukraine
and Kyiv and Chernihiv

00:36:12.657 --> 00:36:15.660
are not just places that
got conquered by Moscow.

00:36:15.660 --> 00:36:19.860
It turns out they're the beginning
of the history of Moscow.

00:36:19.860 --> 00:36:21.690
And that dignifies him,

00:36:21.690 --> 00:36:24.780
and it dignifies his
collegium, his school,

00:36:24.780 --> 00:36:27.960
it dignifies Chernihiv, it dignifies Kyiv.

00:36:27.960 --> 00:36:30.003
That seems like a pretty good play.

00:36:31.131 --> 00:36:34.563
And it worked. For a while, it worked.

00:36:35.573 --> 00:36:39.750
But you can then imagine
what happens next.

00:36:39.750 --> 00:36:42.000
What happens next is that eventually,

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:45.870
the Russian clerics say, take
over the story on their own.

00:36:45.870 --> 00:36:48.000
And they say, "Yes, okay, that's true."

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:52.440
But, after a couple generations,
they pick up all the tricks

00:36:52.440 --> 00:36:54.270
that the Ukrainians use to argue.

00:36:54.270 --> 00:36:55.770
They learn the languages, too.

00:36:55.770 --> 00:36:56.603
They start reading

00:36:56.603 --> 00:36:58.560
the Western religious
literature themselves.

00:36:58.560 --> 00:37:00.600
They learn about theology and disputation.

00:37:00.600 --> 00:37:03.990
And so they take the argument
and they make it their own.

00:37:03.990 --> 00:37:07.050
And then by the 18th century,
it becomes a secular argument,

00:37:07.050 --> 00:37:09.800
no longer a religious argument,
but a secular argument.

00:37:11.460 --> 00:37:13.350
When the Russian Empire is formed to 1721,

00:37:13.350 --> 00:37:16.590
it's called the Russian
Empire for this reason.

00:37:16.590 --> 00:37:20.040
And then when Russia invents
a secular history of itself

00:37:20.040 --> 00:37:22.830
in the 19th century, it's this story.

00:37:22.830 --> 00:37:25.590
But this story happened
because of this guy,

00:37:25.590 --> 00:37:27.180
who, if he drowned under his horse,

00:37:27.180 --> 00:37:28.920
as people tended to do at the time.

00:37:28.920 --> 00:37:30.210
If something had happened to him

00:37:30.210 --> 00:37:32.073
on the way to writing that letter,

00:37:32.970 --> 00:37:34.890
maybe that story would never have arisen.

00:37:34.890 --> 00:37:37.590
And then maybe we would
all analyze this war

00:37:37.590 --> 00:37:38.580
a little bit better than we did.

00:37:38.580 --> 00:37:40.890
And so, again, I'm just
trying to make the point that

00:37:40.890 --> 00:37:43.500
where a certain person is
at a certain time and place

00:37:43.500 --> 00:37:44.760
may matter, actually, a lot.

00:37:44.760 --> 00:37:46.890
Like you couldn't actually
trade Lazar Baranovych off

00:37:46.890 --> 00:37:48.630
for anybody else. He
wasn't interchangeable.

00:37:48.630 --> 00:37:50.670
And those circumstances,

00:37:50.670 --> 00:37:53.790
that Chernihiv fell under
Russia at that particular time,

00:37:53.790 --> 00:37:55.773
were very specific.

00:37:56.880 --> 00:38:01.383
So Chernihiv itself was
bombed in early March.

00:38:04.061 --> 00:38:06.360
I was told by the locals, I
haven't checked this yet myself,

00:38:06.360 --> 00:38:08.520
but the guy who was actually
doing the bombing runs

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:10.740
was himself born in Chernihiv,

00:38:10.740 --> 00:38:12.450
which raises the question
of how you can believe

00:38:12.450 --> 00:38:16.593
different stories about the
place where you're from.

00:38:18.008 --> 00:38:20.400
When I was in the rubble, I was in-

00:38:20.400 --> 00:38:22.740
There was one really terrible bombing run

00:38:22.740 --> 00:38:25.860
which destroyed, or partially destroyed,

00:38:25.860 --> 00:38:30.090
four major apartment
buildings in one neighborhood.

00:38:30.090 --> 00:38:33.000
And when I was there talking to people,

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:34.563
I was struck by a few things.

00:38:37.560 --> 00:38:41.310
Like how, I mean, just like
this place for young people,

00:38:41.310 --> 00:38:45.120
like there was a kid there
who was collecting books.

00:38:45.120 --> 00:38:46.530
He had a book collection.

00:38:46.530 --> 00:38:47.970
And he found an iPhone in the rubble.

00:38:47.970 --> 00:38:49.350
Like he had all these
books and he had an iPhone,

00:38:49.350 --> 00:38:51.900
and as he walked out, he said
to me, "I found an iPhone!"

00:38:51.900 --> 00:38:53.700
Like, this is his childhood.

00:38:53.700 --> 00:38:56.225
But also one thing that struck me is that

00:38:56.225 --> 00:38:59.460
in these apartment buildings,

00:38:59.460 --> 00:39:01.290
people don't necessarily know each other

00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:02.760
or know who they are.

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:03.900
But then after the bombing,

00:39:03.900 --> 00:39:06.030
people did know who one another were,

00:39:06.030 --> 00:39:07.890
because they had to help
each other with things.

00:39:07.890 --> 00:39:10.680
And then it turns out when
a building is destroyed,

00:39:10.680 --> 00:39:12.270
that it has a history.

00:39:12.270 --> 00:39:13.290
One of the reasons you know that is

00:39:13.290 --> 00:39:14.460
that the same kind of bombing

00:39:14.460 --> 00:39:16.950
will destroy different kinds
of buildings in different ways.

00:39:16.950 --> 00:39:21.840
So Soviet-era kommunalka,
or Soviet-era buildings

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:25.290
that were put together from modules,

00:39:25.290 --> 00:39:27.390
are very vulnerable to
bombing, it turns out,

00:39:27.390 --> 00:39:31.020
whereas post-1990s buildings
are generally less so.

00:39:31.020 --> 00:39:34.380
And you can literally see that
worked out before your eyes.

00:39:34.380 --> 00:39:36.270
Or another thing, in
this complex of buildings

00:39:36.270 --> 00:39:38.490
that was destroyed, one
of them, it turns out,

00:39:38.490 --> 00:39:40.650
like this is something you
would never have to know,

00:39:40.650 --> 00:39:43.860
but it turns out that
one of them was built for

00:39:43.860 --> 00:39:48.000
survivors of the nuclear
disaster in Chernobyl.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:51.570
And so they all came down
and they got this building

00:39:51.570 --> 00:39:54.840
as a way of moving away
from where they were.

00:39:54.840 --> 00:39:56.280
But that history would never have come out

00:39:56.280 --> 00:39:57.813
without this other event.

00:39:59.160 --> 00:40:01.530
When I went to the suburbs of Chernihiv,

00:40:01.530 --> 00:40:03.873
I mean, the villages around,

00:40:05.700 --> 00:40:09.205
I talked to a woman who
had five Russian soldiers

00:40:09.205 --> 00:40:11.640
in her house, in her basement.

00:40:11.640 --> 00:40:14.460
And I said, "Okay,
they're Russian soldiers,

00:40:14.460 --> 00:40:17.203
but where were they actually from?"

00:40:17.203 --> 00:40:19.200
Were they Russian, or were they some-

00:40:19.200 --> 00:40:22.770
And she's, "Oh, they were
from Bashkiria and Tatarstan,"

00:40:22.770 --> 00:40:25.620
and I think maybe one of
them was Russian from Russia,

00:40:25.620 --> 00:40:27.270
he was from Siberia.

00:40:27.270 --> 00:40:30.190
And they had a geography.

00:40:30.190 --> 00:40:34.920
They had a notion that Ukraine was Russia.

00:40:34.920 --> 00:40:36.840
But it's a funny kind of geography

00:40:36.840 --> 00:40:39.660
because they're from so far away,

00:40:39.660 --> 00:40:41.700
they're from thousands of
miles away, in some cases.

00:40:41.700 --> 00:40:44.460
And there she is, and they're
all speaking Russian together.

00:40:44.460 --> 00:40:46.140
And she's a native Russian speaker.

00:40:46.140 --> 00:40:48.300
She was talking to me in Russian.

00:40:48.300 --> 00:40:49.770
And they're telling her what Russia is

00:40:49.770 --> 00:40:51.778
and that she's in Russia.

00:40:51.778 --> 00:40:53.040
And there's something
very strange about that,

00:40:53.040 --> 00:40:55.920
but that's their deep geography,

00:40:55.920 --> 00:40:59.883
and there's something about it
which seems to really matter.

00:41:00.810 --> 00:41:02.189
I'm gonna leave you with the last example,

00:41:02.189 --> 00:41:04.539
which I'm sure you probably
already thought of,

00:41:07.080 --> 00:41:09.540
which is Kyiv itself.

00:41:09.540 --> 00:41:13.170
So the way we think about cities

00:41:13.170 --> 00:41:15.450
often has to do with
particular things that happen

00:41:15.450 --> 00:41:16.800
in those cities or in those neighborhoods.

00:41:16.800 --> 00:41:18.750
Like Wannsee might not
mean anything to you,

00:41:18.750 --> 00:41:23.640
but Wannsee is where
a famous plan was made

00:41:23.640 --> 00:41:27.053
for the extermination of the
remaining Jews of Europe.

00:41:27.053 --> 00:41:28.830
It's a part of Berlin.

00:41:28.830 --> 00:41:32.280
And so you, you cannot,
once you know that,

00:41:32.280 --> 00:41:34.470
you can't hear Wannsee
and not think about that.

00:41:34.470 --> 00:41:35.790
Or Vichy.

00:41:35.790 --> 00:41:38.850
So Vichy in France is,

00:41:38.850 --> 00:41:40.380
I mean, there's nice soda
water and everything,

00:41:40.380 --> 00:41:41.970
but it's a spa town,

00:41:41.970 --> 00:41:44.880
but it's also where the
collaborationist government

00:41:44.880 --> 00:41:46.860
had its capital during
the Second World War.

00:41:46.860 --> 00:41:48.750
And so Vichy means that.

00:41:48.750 --> 00:41:51.330
It's very hard to take
that away from Vichy.

00:41:51.330 --> 00:41:52.980
I would suggest that there's going to be

00:41:52.980 --> 00:41:56.670
a little something around Kyiv like that,

00:41:56.670 --> 00:41:58.560
but in a positive sense,

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:01.023
because Zelensky stayed.

00:42:01.860 --> 00:42:03.480
If Zelensky had left,
many things, I think,

00:42:03.480 --> 00:42:05.610
would be different, in
the world and in our minds

00:42:05.610 --> 00:42:07.170
and in this class, probably.

00:42:07.170 --> 00:42:10.500
But he stayed, and I think that makes Kyiv

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:13.950
mean something different than
it would've otherwise been.

00:42:13.950 --> 00:42:16.110
In other words, I'm trying to suggest that

00:42:16.110 --> 00:42:18.120
this deep geography, although it's real,

00:42:18.120 --> 00:42:21.960
is also fungible, it's changeable.

00:42:21.960 --> 00:42:24.603
It can be altered by human action.

00:42:26.040 --> 00:42:27.840
I'm thinking in particular
about the night,

00:42:27.840 --> 00:42:29.010
a couple of nights into the war,

00:42:29.010 --> 00:42:31.310
where he made the selfie
video, where he said,

00:42:32.347 --> 00:42:33.757
"President tooth."

00:42:33.757 --> 00:42:34.740
"I'm here."

00:42:34.740 --> 00:42:36.180
And then he goes on,
"My advisors are here.

00:42:36.180 --> 00:42:37.320
We're all here. We're all right here."

00:42:37.320 --> 00:42:40.230
And he was countering Russian propaganda,

00:42:40.230 --> 00:42:42.630
which had said he had
fled. That's part of it.

00:42:42.630 --> 00:42:44.017
But also, he was saying,

00:42:44.017 --> 00:42:48.387
"I'm here, I'm going to
stay. I'm reassuring people."

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:52.810
And this is just my last
example of the point that

00:42:53.670 --> 00:42:56.550
maybe places and people
aren't so interchangeable.

00:42:56.550 --> 00:43:00.150
That it matters a great deal
that when he said, "I am here,"

00:43:00.150 --> 00:43:02.010
the buildings behind him were Kyiv,

00:43:02.010 --> 00:43:04.403
and not Lvov and not Warsaw.

00:43:04.403 --> 00:43:07.620
That everyone in Kyiv,
when he said, "I am here,"

00:43:07.620 --> 00:43:10.500
could recognize where he was in Kyiv.

00:43:13.695 --> 00:43:17.550
And that "I'm here" was also the counter

00:43:17.550 --> 00:43:22.550
to a different kind of deep geography.

00:43:22.830 --> 00:43:24.720
Because at the moment when he said that,

00:43:24.720 --> 00:43:27.150
there still were bombs falling in Kyiv

00:43:27.150 --> 00:43:28.710
which were meant for him.

00:43:28.710 --> 00:43:31.020
And there were still groups of assassins

00:43:31.020 --> 00:43:34.020
moving towards Kyiv, or actually
inside the city of Kyiv,

00:43:34.020 --> 00:43:35.970
who were meant to kill him.

00:43:35.970 --> 00:43:38.400
And they were operating under
a different deep geography,

00:43:38.400 --> 00:43:41.490
deep geography which
goes something like this.

00:43:41.490 --> 00:43:43.200
And I'm not, I don't have to invent this

00:43:43.200 --> 00:43:46.950
because it's what Putin
said in in 2021, 2022,

00:43:46.950 --> 00:43:50.130
that Russia and Ukraine
have always been one place,

00:43:50.130 --> 00:43:53.640
and the people who say that
Ukraine is a different place,

00:43:53.640 --> 00:43:55.380
they are somehow exotic.

00:43:55.380 --> 00:43:57.000
They somehow come from the outside.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:43:58.260
They're Hapsburgs, they're Poles,

00:43:58.260 --> 00:43:59.940
they're Europeans, they're Americans.

00:43:59.940 --> 00:44:02.610
And therefore anyone who
says that there's a Ukraine,

00:44:02.610 --> 00:44:04.380
there's something flawed
about that person.

00:44:04.380 --> 00:44:05.820
They don't belong there.

00:44:05.820 --> 00:44:08.043
They simply need to be removed.

00:44:08.940 --> 00:44:10.770
And we'll remove them lexically,

00:44:10.770 --> 00:44:13.410
by calling them Nazis
or whatever it takes.

00:44:13.410 --> 00:44:15.090
But we're also going
remove them physically.

00:44:15.090 --> 00:44:16.890
Because if we remove them physically,

00:44:16.890 --> 00:44:19.750
then the rest of the Ukrainian
people will go along with us,

00:44:19.750 --> 00:44:21.480
and the war will be over.

00:44:21.480 --> 00:44:23.259
That is a kind of deep geography.

00:44:23.259 --> 00:44:27.240
And that deep geography
animated the attempt

00:44:27.240 --> 00:44:31.410
to take Kyiv and to kill this person.

00:44:31.410 --> 00:44:34.620
So I had a lot of time
to think about that,

00:44:34.620 --> 00:44:36.900
because if you're visiting the President,

00:44:36.900 --> 00:44:39.150
it takes a long time to
get there, obviously.

00:44:39.150 --> 00:44:40.740
Because like, they lead you
here and they lead you there,

00:44:40.740 --> 00:44:42.390
and then you're never
gonna find your way out.

00:44:42.390 --> 00:44:45.030
They lead you here, it's
all dark and confusing,

00:44:45.030 --> 00:44:46.140
and there are lots of checkpoints,

00:44:46.140 --> 00:44:48.000
and there're lots of barriers and things.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:49.650
And so it gets you to think,

00:44:49.650 --> 00:44:53.970
how important is it actually
that this person is right here,

00:44:53.970 --> 00:44:55.680
as opposed to another person right here,

00:44:55.680 --> 00:44:59.460
or this person being somewhere else?

00:44:59.460 --> 00:45:01.530
So, the deep geography is important.

00:45:01.530 --> 00:45:04.080
That was the point of this.

00:45:04.080 --> 00:45:08.010
But also the deep
geography can be changed.

00:45:08.010 --> 00:45:10.350
The deep geography can
be changed by action

00:45:10.350 --> 00:45:13.470
and by experience and by renaming.

00:45:13.470 --> 00:45:16.923
And I was thinking about that,
I think about that as well.

00:45:18.881 --> 00:45:22.740
I was there during this last,
this Kharkiv counteroffensive,

00:45:22.740 --> 00:45:25.230
when the Ukrainians took
back almost all of Kharkiv.

00:45:25.230 --> 00:45:27.060
And of course, that
means that Kharkiv Oblast

00:45:27.060 --> 00:45:29.520
now means something different
than it did a few days ago.

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:31.200
And for the men and women

00:45:31.200 --> 00:45:32.520
who were involved in that offensive,

00:45:32.520 --> 00:45:36.180
it's gonna mean something
different to them as well.

00:45:36.180 --> 00:45:40.074
And that the fact that

00:45:40.074 --> 00:45:41.970
so many Ukrainians

00:45:41.970 --> 00:45:45.723
have had to move during
this war, for bad reasons,

00:45:47.070 --> 00:45:49.723
4 million deported to Russia,

00:45:49.723 --> 00:45:54.723
well over 10 million crossed a
Western border and come back,

00:45:55.170 --> 00:45:56.400
people inside the country,

00:45:56.400 --> 00:45:58.650
well over half the population has moved

00:45:58.650 --> 00:45:59.550
in one way or another.

00:45:59.550 --> 00:46:04.380
And that moving is associated
with the changing of meanings.

00:46:04.380 --> 00:46:08.400
And sometimes it's associated
with a change in meanings

00:46:08.400 --> 00:46:09.792
in a positive sense.

00:46:09.792 --> 00:46:11.640
This is just the very last thought.

00:46:11.640 --> 00:46:13.788
But I was really struck,

00:46:13.788 --> 00:46:15.360
I mean, I'm not trying to
make a happy story of this,

00:46:15.360 --> 00:46:16.770
because of course it's not a happy story,

00:46:16.770 --> 00:46:19.410
but I was really struck by how,

00:46:19.410 --> 00:46:22.530
when people talked about
all of this movement,

00:46:22.530 --> 00:46:23.910
whether it was the President himself,

00:46:23.910 --> 00:46:25.470
or whether it was some of
the soldiers I talked to,

00:46:25.470 --> 00:46:26.760
or whether it was some
of the people in villages

00:46:26.760 --> 00:46:29.989
that I talked to, when they
talked about all this movement,

00:46:29.989 --> 00:46:32.970
they had interpretations of it,

00:46:32.970 --> 00:46:36.870
that like this in some
way shows who we are.

00:46:36.870 --> 00:46:41.870
The fact that we went away and came back,

00:46:42.300 --> 00:46:46.470
The fact that we were
able, or have already-

00:46:46.470 --> 00:46:48.900
a lot of people have already
rebuilt their houses,

00:46:48.900 --> 00:46:50.580
the fact that we rebuilt,

00:46:50.580 --> 00:46:52.680
the fact that we got back to Kharkiv,

00:46:52.680 --> 00:46:54.870
the fact that Zelensky stayed,

00:46:54.870 --> 00:46:59.130
that these things say something
about us, about who we are.

00:46:59.130 --> 00:47:01.410
We can be pushed, we can be pulled,

00:47:01.410 --> 00:47:03.870
but then where we choose to be in the end,

00:47:03.870 --> 00:47:05.820
says something about us.

00:47:05.820 --> 00:47:06.960
That we choose to fight this war,

00:47:06.960 --> 00:47:09.480
that we choose to help the
people fighting this war,

00:47:09.480 --> 00:47:10.770
that we choose to make it through somehow,

00:47:10.770 --> 00:47:13.050
says something about us.

00:47:13.050 --> 00:47:13.883
And so in that sense,

00:47:13.883 --> 00:47:16.650
like this thing that
people are talking about

00:47:16.650 --> 00:47:18.390
as the formation of a nation,
I think, is not quite right.

00:47:18.390 --> 00:47:19.560
The nation was already there.

00:47:19.560 --> 00:47:21.900
But how people think about their nation,

00:47:21.900 --> 00:47:24.810
and particularly what they
think it means to be free,

00:47:24.810 --> 00:47:27.210
and what it's worth sacrificing about,

00:47:27.210 --> 00:47:28.800
you can also connect that to space.

00:47:28.800 --> 00:47:30.686
In fact, I guess my point would be,

00:47:30.686 --> 00:47:33.390
you almost have to connect it to space.

00:47:33.390 --> 00:47:36.870
It's hard to imagine people
having a story about themselves

00:47:36.870 --> 00:47:38.952
which involves risk and values,

00:47:38.952 --> 00:47:42.630
which doesn't also in
some way involve space.

00:47:42.630 --> 00:47:44.980
And that's where I'm
gonna leave it. Thank you.

